items.abstract:
<jats:title>ABSTRACT</jats:title>
				<jats:p>
					<jats:italic>Water-lubricated bearings have been applied to support ship screw shafts for over a hundered years.</jats:italic>
					<jats:italic>Development of plastic materials has caused that novel sliding polymers appeared available on the market</jats:italic>
					<jats:italic>and being approved by classification institutions, possible to be applied in shipbuilding. However in the</jats:italic>
					<jats:italic>subject - matter literature there is no reference to application of bearings fitted with metal or ceramic</jats:italic>
					<jats:italic>bushes in shipbuilding. Nevertheless they have important merits such as low resistance to motion, long</jats:italic>
					<jats:italic>service life or stability of form. But some doubts are evoked by their large value of shape elasticity module</jats:italic>
					<jats:italic>which can lead to local stress concentration at the bush edges in the case of non-axiality of bush and shaft</jats:italic>
					<jats:italic>axes. Hence this work has been aimed at the testing of a bearing made of bronze-graphite silter. In the</jats:italic>
					<jats:italic>work is presented a comparison of measurement results of resistance to motion , hydrodynamic pressure</jats:italic>
					<jats:italic>distributions in lubricating film as well as shaft axis trajectories of the bearing, with those made for a typical</jats:italic>
					<jats:italic>elastic polymer bearing. The measurement results have showed high quality of the tested material. In the</jats:italic>
					<jats:italic>opinion of these authors it could be applicable to bearing ship propeller shafts.</jats:italic>
				</jats:p>
title: Assessment of possible application of waterlubricated sintered brass slide bearing for marine propeller shaft

items.abstract:
<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>
<jats:p>This paper presents optimization of selected combined diesel engine-steam turbine systems. Two systems: the system combined with waste heat one-pressure boiler only and its version containing additionally low-pressure boiler proper feeding degasifier and the system of two-pressure cycle, were taken into considerations. Their surplus values of power output and efficiency associated with utilization of waste heat contained in piston engine exhaust gas were compared to each other. For the considerations two high-power low-speed engines were taken into account. The main engines of comparable power of about 54 MW produced by Wartsila and MAN Diesel & Turbo firms, were selected.</jats:p>
title: Selected Combined Power Systems Consisted of Self-Ignition Engine and Steam Turbine
